# Multi-Agent Coordination — Claude · Codex · Gemini · Cursor

This handbook defines how the planning, implementation, review, and editing agents work together. By treating each agent as a specialized micro-service, we maintain a clean codebase, avoid merge conflicts, and enforce quality control.

---

## 1. Roles & Lanes (The Roster)

Each agent has a specific comparative advantage. Do not use them outside their lane.

| Agent | Role | Scope / Lane | Primary Function |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Claude** | Architect / Planner | `docs/specs/**` | Analyzes requirements, designs specs, creates Codex Task Packets. |
| **Codex** | Developer | `src/**`, `tests/**`, `scripts/**` | Implements the code on a clean branch, runs verification gates. |
| **Gemini** | Critic / Reviewer | read-only; `docs/reviews/**` | Audits merged builds, runs full test gates, recommends improvements. |
| **Cursor** | IDE / Surgeon | Whole Project | Visual command center. Slices code changes, reviews diffs, styles UI. |

---

## 2. The Multi-Agent Pipeline

The development loop starts with planning, moves to implementation, runs validation, executes peer review, and returns to the IDE for final refinement.

```
                  ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
                  │ 1. Plan the feature                    │
                  │    - Claude writes docs/specs/*.md     │
                  └────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                      │
                                      ▼
                  ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
                  │ 2. Implementation                      │
                  │    - Codex runs in isolated worktree   │
                  │    - Passes dev_check.sh fast          │
                  └────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                      │
                                      ▼
                  ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
                  │ 3. Automated Peer Review               │
                  │    - Gemini runs dev_check.sh full     │
                  │    - Generates docs/reviews/review-*.md│
                  └────────────────────────────────────────┘
                                      │
                                      ▼
                  ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
                  │ 4. Refine & Polish                     │
                  │    - Human reviews Gemini's audit      │
                  │    - Cursor agent edits UI & code      │
                  └────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## 3. Workflow Commands & Handoffs

 Handoffs are processed via a local, file-based queue managed by `scripts/agent_workflow.sh`.

### Step 1: Hand off from Claude to Codex (Development)
After Claude designs the spec and you approve it, submit it to the queue:
```bash
./scripts/agent_workflow.sh handoff submit docs/my-feature_DEV_PLAN.md --agent codex --mode local-worktree
```
This checks out a clean branch `agent/codex/my-feature` in an isolated Git worktree `../<project>-my-feature` and triggers `scripts/codex_auto_dev.sh` to implement it.

### Step 2: Hand off from Codex to Gemini (Review)
Once Codex completes implementation, passes the fast gate, and merges, Codex submits a review job to the queue:
```bash
./scripts/agent_workflow.sh handoff submit docs/my-feature_DEV_PLAN.md --agent gemini --mode local
```
This triggers `scripts/gemini_auto_review.sh` to pull `main`, run the full test suite (`./scripts/dev_check.sh full`), and output a multi-axis audit to `docs/reviews/my-feature-YYYY-MM-DD.md`.

---

## 4. Worktree Isolation & Cleanup

To prevent agents from colliding or blocking your active development inside Cursor, agents work in isolated worktrees:
*   Use `scripts/agent_worktree.sh create <slug>` to spin up a worktree.
*   Use `scripts/worktree_doctor.sh` to automatically kill zombie Node/API processes and prune stale directories.
*   Use `scripts/notify_slack.sh` to update your Slack developer channel about progress.
